<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-322-930  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 322 930.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 1 1989 n1166 p1(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fraud victims collude in crime cover-up.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collins, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Publicly-traded firms in Great Britain are colluding withcriminals accused of computer fraud to cover up the crime.andP;  Alegal document obtained by Computer Weekly states that thecriminal, in return for escaping prosecution, will repay the50,000 pounds sterling embezzled from a financial institution.andO;The firm is allowed to report the loss to the insurer but will notreport it to the police or other third party.andP;  Some Britishinsurance companies, such as Lloyd's, will pay out withoutrequiring the company to inform the police.andP;  London Policeofficials are frustrated by this move as they feel it encouragesorganized crime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EnglandComputer CrimesLegal IssuesFraudInsurance.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>